        <!-- ===== 05 · HOWRAISE ===== -->
        <section id="howraise" class="sec">
          <h2>How do we hand-raise an African Grey, week by week?</h2>
          <p class="opener">Hand-raising a grey well is a fourteen-week job, not a marketing word — a rhythm of feeding, handling and patient weaning that we run the same way for every chick. Because rushing any stage produces a nervous adult, we let each bird set its own pace and only call it ready when it's eating on its own and emotionally settled.</p>
          <img class="sec-img inf-img" src={IMG + "spoonfed-african-grey-baby-hand-feeding.webp"} srcset={IMG + "spoonfed-african-grey-baby-hand-feeding-760.webp 760w, " + IMG + "spoonfed-african-grey-baby-hand-feeding.webp 1408w"} sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" alt="Spoon-feeding a baby African Grey chick by hand in our home — the daily hand-feeding that makes a grey hand-raised, not just hand-fed" />
          <h3>From brooder to weaning: the 12-to-16-week timeline</h3>
          <img class="sec-img inf-img" src={IMG + "how-we-hand-raise-weaning-timeline.webp"} srcset={IMG + "how-we-hand-raise-weaning-timeline-760.webp 760w, " + IMG + "how-we-hand-raise-weaning-timeline.webp 1408w"} sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" alt="Timeline of how C.A.Gs hand-raises an African Grey from hatch through brooder, hand-feeding and weaning at 12 to 16 weeks to ready for home" />
          <div class="otA">
            <div class="otrow"><span class="ot-k">Hatch → 3 weeks</span><span class="ot-v">Brooder warmth, frequent hand-feeding, first daily handling</span></div>
            <div class="otrow"><span class="ot-k">3 → 8 weeks</span><span class="ot-v">Feather growth, household sounds, more time out on hands</span></div>
            <div class="otrow"><span class="ot-k">8 → 12 weeks</span><span class="ot-v">Exploring solid foods, fledging, confidence-building play</span></div>
            <div class="otrow"><span class="ot-k">12 → 16 weeks</span><span class="ot-v">Self-weaning onto pellets &amp; chop, then cleared to go home</span></div>
          </div>
          <h4>At what age is a hand-raised grey ready to come home?</h4>
          <p>When it is fully weaned and eating independently — typically between 12 and 16 weeks — and not a day sooner. A weaned grey travels better, settles faster, and starts its new life confident instead of frightened.</p>
          <h5>Why we never release an unweaned or force-weaned chick</h5>
          <p>Selling an unweaned baby shifts the hardest, riskiest job — hand-feeding formula at the right temperature and consistency — onto a new owner who's never done it, and force-weaning to hit a sale date can scar a grey for life. We simply don't do either, however keen a buyer is to take one early.</p>
          <h6>Breeder note: our daily weaning-weight log</h6>
          <p>Every chick is weighed daily through weaning, because a grey that's quietly dropping grams tells you it isn't ready long before it looks unwell. That log is another thing we'll gladly show you before you commit.</p>
          <h3>How we socialize a grey across a whole household</h3>
          <p>From the first weeks we make sure several people handle each chick — different voices, different hands, the normal noise of a family home — so the grey grows up used to more than one person. That habit is the quiet reason our birds tend to settle into families rather than fixate on a single owner.</p>
          <p><a href="https://lafeber.com/vet/basic-information-sheet-for-the-african-grey-parrot/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">LafeberVet's African Grey information sheet ↗</a> sets out the same weaning and nutrition fundamentals we raise to, if you'd like a veterinary second opinion on how a grey should be brought up.</p>
          <p class="ticket"><a href="#reserve" class="ticket-cta">Reserve a weaned, hand-raised grey <span>→</span></a></p>
        </section>

