        <!-- ===== 06 · DOWNSIDE ===== -->
        <section id="downside" class="sec">
          <h2>What's the honest downside of a hand-raised grey?</h2>
          <p class="opener">Here's the part most sellers skip: a hand-raised grey bonds so readily that it can over-attach to one person if you let it. Because we'd rather you succeed than just sell you a bird, we build against that from the nursery — and we tell you how to keep it from happening at home.</p>
          <img class="sec-img inf-img" src={IMG + "prevent-one-person-bird.webp"} srcset={IMG + "prevent-one-person-bird-760.webp 760w, " + IMG + "prevent-one-person-bird.webp 1408w"} sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" alt="How rotating handling prevents a hand-raised African Grey from over-bonding to one person and keeps it a family bird" />
          <h3>The over-bonding risk sellers don't mention</h3>
          <p>A grey that adores exactly one human and bites everyone else isn't broken — it's usually a bird that only ever knew one pair of hands. Left unmanaged, that pattern narrows a family's bird down to a single-person pet.</p>
          <h4>How do we prevent a one-person bird?</h4>
          <p>We rotate handling across several people from the very start, so "people" — plural — is normal to the chick long before it comes home. Then we ask you to keep the rotation going for the first months.</p>
          <h5>Example: why Amie steps up for strangers, not just us</h5>
          <p>Amie is the clearest proof — because Teri, Mark and visitors all handled her through weaning, she'll step up for a guest she met five minutes ago. That isn't luck; it's the rotation, and it's a habit any household can keep.</p>
        </section>

