        <section id="scams" class="sec">
          <h2>How do you spot a "fake hand-raised" listing?</h2>
          <p class="opener">A fake "hand-raised" listing follows a script, and once you know it you can read one in seconds — sub-floor price, no papers, no live video, untraceable payment. Because we're a real aviary that competes against these fakes, calling out the pattern protects you and it protects our name.</p>
          <img class="sec-img inf-img" src={IMG + "fake-hand-raised-listing-red-flags.webp"} srcset={IMG + "fake-hand-raised-listing-red-flags-760.webp 760w, " + IMG + "fake-hand-raised-listing-red-flags.webp 1408w"} sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" alt="Five red flags of a fake hand-raised African Grey listing: price under $1,500, no CITES papers, refuses a live video call, Zelle or gift cards only, no weaning date given" />
          <h3>The red flags of a fake hand-raised seller</h3>
          <p>Any single flag is a caution; two or more together, and you should close the tab. The scam pattern is remarkably consistent across the fake farms we track.</p>
          <h4>How can you tell a real hand-raised grey from a stolen photo?</h4>
          <p>You ask the listing to do something a photo can't — move, in real time, on your schedule.</p>
