        <!-- ===== 09 · WHY ===== -->
        <section id="why" class="sec">
          <h2>Why are African Greys such remarkable companion birds?</h2>
          <p class="opener">African Greys earn their reputation honestly — they're arguably the most cognitively gifted parrots kept as companions, and a hand-raised one turns that intelligence toward you. Because a grey is a decades-long relationship, that talking, problem-solving mind is the reason the commitment is worth it.</p>
          <img class="sec-img inf-img" src={IMG + "why-african-greys-exceptional.webp"} srcset={IMG + "why-african-greys-exceptional-760.webp 760w, " + IMG + "why-african-greys-exceptional.webp 1408w"} sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" alt="Four traits that make hand-raised African Greys exceptional: talks 100+ words, highly intelligent, bonds for life, lives 40+ years" />
          <h3>Talking ability, intelligence, and lifelong bonding</h3>
          <p>Greys routinely learn scores of words and use them in context, solve puzzles that stump other parrots, and form deep, lasting bonds. Hand-raising doesn't create that intelligence — it opens the door so the bird will share it with you rather than guard against you.</p>
          <p><a href="https://parrots.org/encyclopedia/grey-parrot/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The World Parrot Trust's grey parrot profile ↗</a> catalogs the cognition research behind that reputation, and hand-raising is simply what turns all of it toward you instead of away.</p>
        </section>

