        <!-- ===== 12 · INCLUDED · K3 green ledger ===== -->
        <section id="included" class="sec">
          <h2>What comes home with your hand-raised African Grey?</h2>
          <p class="opener">Every grey leaves with the full paper trail that separates a real breeder from a fake — not as a bonus, but as proof. Because that documentation is exactly what a fraudulent seller can never assemble, it's also the fastest way for you to confirm you bought the real thing.</p>
          <img class="sec-img inf-img" src={IMG + "what-comes-home-hand-raised-grey.webp"} srcset={IMG + "what-comes-home-hand-raised-grey-760.webp 760w, " + IMG + "what-comes-home-hand-raised-grey.webp 1408w"} sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" alt="What comes home with a hand-raised African Grey: CITES papers, DNA certificate, closed leg band, avian-vet health record, PBFD and Polyomavirus PCR results, plus a care guide" />
          <div class="k3">
            <ul class="k3-list">
              <li><b>CITES captive-bred papers</b> — Appendix I, legal to own and rehome in the U.S.</li>
              <li><b>DNA-sexing certificate</b> — your grey's sex, confirmed by lab.</li>
              <li><b>Closed leg band</b> — captive-bred identification.</li>
              <li><b>Avian-vet health record</b> — examined before it flies.</li>
              <li><b>PBFD &amp; Avian Polyomavirus PCR</b> — screened, with results.</li>
              <li><b>Care guide, welcome kit &amp; lifetime support</b> — we stay reachable.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <h3>The documentation stack on every bird</h3>
          <p>Each document is one you can verify independently, which is the whole point — you shouldn't have to take a stranger's word about a $2,000 bird.</p>
          <h4>Why does CITES paperwork matter for a captive-bred grey?</h4>
          <p>Because African Greys are CITES Appendix I, the paperwork is what proves your bird is a legal, captive-bred companion rather than a wild-caught import — it protects you as much as the species.</p>
          <h5>What Appendix I means for owning and moving your bird</h5>
          <p>Appendix I birds are legal to own and transfer within the United States when the captive-bred documentation is in order, which ours always is. It also means a legitimate breeder never offers to smuggle one overseas.</p>
          <h6>Citation: CITES Appendix I captive-bred transfer rules</h6>
          <p><a href="https://cites.org/eng/app/index.php" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The official CITES appendices ↗</a> set out exactly how Appendix-I captive-bred birds must be documented — the international rules our own paperwork is built to satisfy.</p>
        </section>

        <div class="seam-wrap" role="presentation"><img class="seam" src={seam} alt="" loading="lazy" width="182" height="60" /></div>

        <!-- ===== 13 · HEALTH ===== -->
        <section id="health" class="sec">
          <h2>Is your hand-raised grey health-screened before it flies?</h2>
          <p class="opener">Yes — every grey is seen by an avian vet and PCR-screened before it travels, because shipping a bird that isn't well is unthinkable to us. That screening, paired with the health record in the folder, is how you know the grey that lands is the grey we described.</p>
          <img class="sec-img inf-img" src={IMG + "hand-raised-grey-health-pcr-screening.webp"} srcset={IMG + "hand-raised-grey-health-pcr-screening-760.webp 760w, " + IMG + "hand-raised-grey-health-pcr-screening.webp 1408w"} sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" alt="Health screening on every hand-raised African Grey before shipping: avian-vet health check, PBFD PCR screened, Avian Polyomavirus PCR, and closed leg-band identification" />
          <h3>Our health check and PBFD / Polyomavirus PCR screening</h3>
          <p>Each grey gets an avian-vet examination and PCR screening for PBFD and Avian Polyomavirus, and you receive the results with your bird. If your own avian vet ever flags a covered concern after arrival, we want the call — we stand behind the birds we raise.</p>
          <p><a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12560886/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">A veterinary review of psittacine beak and feather disease ↗</a> explains why PBFD is the one result every serious grey buyer wants ruled out — which is precisely what our screening does.</p>
          <p><a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11939742/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Research on PCR-based molecular sexing ↗</a> is why the sex printed on your grey's certificate is a lab result rather than a guess about a visually monomorphic bird.</p>
